{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28b672394ffe2uI216TSFvnXtq","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d7498dcee001vFSESYQXuYlorA","parts":[{"id":"prt_d7498f0fe001sBHYXQSVgI0oMm","messageID":"msg_d7498dcee001vFSESYQXuYlorA","sessionID":"ses_28b672394ffe2uI216TSFvnXtq","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5b684dee91bc4010ba35cedc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/AGENTS.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/AGENTS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # AGENTS.md\n2: \n3: This file provides guidance to AI agents (e.g., Claude Code, Cursor, and other LLM-powered tools) when working with code in this repository.\n4: \n5: ## Project Overview\n6: \n7: tmuxp is a session manager for tmux that allows users to save and load tmux sessions through YAML/JSON configuration files. It's powered by libtmux and provides a declarative way to manage tmux sessions.\n8: \n9: ## Development Commands\n10: \n11: ### Testing\n12: - `just test` or `uv run py.test` - Run all tests\n13: - `uv run py.test tests/path/to/test.py::TestClass::test_method` - Run a single test\n14: - `uv run ptw .` - Continuous test runner with pytest-watcher\n15: - `uv run ptw . --now --doctest-modules` - Watch tests including doctests\n16: - `just start` or `just watch-test` - Watch and run tests on file changes\n17: \n18: ### Code Quality\n19: - `just ruff` or `uv run ruff check .` - Run linter\n20: - `uv run ruff check . --fix --show-fixes` - Fix linting issues automatically\n21: - `just ruff-format` or `uv run ruff format .` - Format code\n22: - `just mypy` or `uv run mypy` - Run type checking (strict mode enabled)\n23: - `just watch-ruff` - Watch and lint on changes\n24: - `just watch-mypy` - Watch and type check on changes\n25: \n26: ### Documentation\n27: - `just build-docs` - Build documentation\n28: - `just serve-docs` - Serve docs locally at http://localhost:8013\n29: - `just dev-docs` - Watch and serve docs with auto-reload\n30: - `just start-docs` - Alternative to dev_docs\n31: \n32: ### CLI Commands\n33: - `tmuxp load <config>` - Load a tmux session from config\n34: - `tmuxp load -d <config>` - Load session in detached state\n35: - `tmuxp freeze <session-name>` - Export running session to config\n36: - `tmuxp convert <file>` - Convert between YAML and JSON\n37: - `tmuxp shell` - Interactive Python shell with tmux context\n38: - `tmuxp debug-info` - Collect system info for debugging\n39: \n40: ## Architecture\n41: \n42: ### Core Components\n43: \n44: 1. **CLI Module** (`src/tmuxp/cli/`): Entry points for all tmuxp commands\n45:    - `load.py`: Load tmux sessions from config files\n46:    - `freeze.py`: Export live sessions to config files\n47:    - `convert.py`: Convert between YAML/JSON formats\n48:    - `shell.py`: Interactive Python shell with tmux context\n49: \n50: 2. **Workspace Module** (`src/tmuxp/workspace/`): Core session management\n51:    - `builder.py`: Builds tmux sessions from configuration\n52:    - `loader.py`: Loads and validates config files\n53:    - `finders.py`: Locates workspace config files\n54:    - `freezer.py`: Exports running sessions to config\n55: \n56: 3. **Plugin System** (`src/tmuxp/plugin.py`): Extensibility framework\n57:    - Plugins extend `TmuxpPlugin` base class\n58:    - Hooks: `before_workspace_builder`, `on_window_create`, `after_window_finished`, `before_script`, `reattach`\n59:    - Version constraint checking for compatibility\n60: \n61: ### Configuration Flow\n62: \n63: 1. Load YAML/JSON config via `ConfigReader` (handles includes, environment variables)\n64: 2. Expand inline shorthand syntax\n65: 3. Trickle down default values (session → window → pane)\n66: 4. Validate configuration structure\n67: 5. Build tmux session via `WorkspaceBuilder`\n68: \n69: ### Key Patterns\n70: \n71: - **Type Safety**: All code uses type hints with mypy strict mode\n72: - **Error Handling**: Custom exception hierarchy based on `TmuxpException`\n73: - **Testing**: Pytest with fixtures for tmux server/session/window/pane isolation\n74: - **Future Imports**: All files use `from __future__ import annotations`\n75: \n76: ## Configuration Format\n77: \n78: ```yaml\n79: session_name: my-session\n80: start_directory: ~/project\n81: windows:\n82:   - window_name: editor\n83:     layout: main-vertical\n84:     panes:\n85:       - shell_command:\n86:           - vim\n87:       - shell_command:\n88:           - git status\n89: ```\n90: \n91: ## Environment Variables\n92: \n93: - `TMUXP_CONFIGDIR`: Custom directory for workspace configs\n94: - `TMUX_CONF`: Path to tmux configuration file\n95: - `TMUXP_DEFAULT_COLUMNS/ROWS`: Default session dimensions\n96: \n97: ## Testing Guidelines\n98: \n99: - **Use functional tests only**: Write tests as standalone functions, not classes. Avoid `class TestFoo:` groupings - use descriptive function names and file organization instead.\n100: - Use pytest fixtures from `tests/fixtures/` for tmux objects\n101: - Test plugins using mock packages in `tests/fixtures/pluginsystem/`\n102: - Use `retry_until` utilities for async tmux operations\n103: - Run single tests with: `uv run py.test tests/file.py::test_function_name`\n104: - **Use libtmux fixtures**: Prefer `server`, `session`, `window`, `pane` fixtures over manual setup\n105: - **Avoid mocks when fixtures exist**: Use real tmux fixtures instead of `MagicMock`\n106: - **Use `tmp_path`** fixture instead of Python's `tempfile`\n107: - **Use `monkeypatch`** fixture instead of `unittest.mock`\n108: \n109: ## Code Style\n110: \n111: - Follow NumPy-style docstrings (pydocstyle convention)\n112: - Use ruff for formatting and linting\n113: - Maintain strict mypy type checking\n114: - Keep imports organized with future annotations at top\n115: - **Prefer namespace imports for stdlib**: Use `import enum` and `enum.Enum` instead of `from enum import Enum`; third-party packages may use `from X import Y`\n116: - **Type imports**: Use `import typing as t` and access via namespace (e.g., `t.Optional`)\n117: - **Development workflow**: Format → Test → Commit → Lint/Type Check → Test → Final Commit\n118: \n119: ## Git Commit Standards\n120: \n121: Format commit messages as:\n122: ```\n123: Scope(type[detail]): concise description\n124: \n125: why: Explanation of necessity or impact.\n126: what:\n127: - Specific technical changes made\n128: - Focused on a single topic\n129: ```\n130: \n131: Common commit types:\n132: - **feat**: New features or enhancements\n133: - **fix**: Bug fixes\n134: - **refactor**: Code restructuring without functional change\n135: - **docs**: Documentation updates\n136: - **chore**: Maintenance (dependencies, tooling, config)\n137: - **test**: Test-related updates\n138: - **style**: Code style and formatting\n139: - **py(deps)**: Dependencies\n140: - **py(deps[dev])**: Dev Dependencies\n141: - **ai(rules[AGENTS])**: AI rule updates\n142: - **ai(claude[rules])**: Claude Code rules (CLAUDE.md)\n143: - **ai(claude[command])**: Claude Code command changes\n144: \n145: Example:\n146: ```\n147: Pane(feat[send_keys]): Add support for literal flag\n148: \n149: why: Enable sending literal characters without tmux interpretation\n150: what:\n151: - Add literal parameter to send_keys method\n152: - Update send_keys to pass -l flag when literal=True\n153: - Add tests for literal key sending\n154: ```\n155: For multi-line commits, use heredoc to preserve formatting:\n156: ```bash\n157: git commit -m \"$(cat <<'EOF'\n158: feat(Component[method]) add feature description\n159: \n160: why: Explanation of the change.\n161: what:\n162: - First change\n163: - Second change\n164: EOF\n165: )\"\n166: ```\n167: \n168: ## Logging Standards\n169: \n170: These rules guide future logging changes; existing code may not yet conform.\n171: \n172: ### Logger setup\n173: \n174: - Use `logging.getLogger(__name__)` in every module\n175: - Add `NullHandler` in library `__init__.py` files\n176: - Never configure handlers, levels, or formatters in library code — that's the application's job\n177: \n178: ### Structured context via `extra`\n179: \n180: Pass structured data on every log call where useful for filtering, searching, or test assertions.\n181: \n182: **Core keys** (stable, scalar, safe at any log level):\n183: \n184: | Key | Type | Context |\n185: |-----|------|---------|\n186: | `tmux_cmd` | `str` | tmux command line |\n187: | `tmux_subcommand` | `str` | tmux subcommand (e.g. `new-session`) |\n188: | `tmux_target` | `str` | tmux target specifier (e.g. `mysession:1.2`) |\n189: | `tmux_exit_code` | `int` | tmux process exit code |\n190: | `tmux_session` | `str` | session name |\n191: | `tmux_window` | `str` | window name or index |\n192: | `tmux_pane` | `str` | pane identifier |\n193: | `tmux_config_path` | `str` | workspace config file path |\n194: | `tmux_layout` | `str` | window layout string |\n195: \n196: **Heavy/optional keys** (DEBUG only, potentially large):\n197: \n198: | Key | Type | Context |\n199: |-----|------|---------|\n200: | `tmux_stdout` | `list[str]` | tmux stdout lines (truncate or cap; `%(tmux_stdout)s` produces repr) |\n201: | `tmux_stderr` | `list[str]` | tmux stderr lines (same caveats) |\n202: \n203: Treat established keys as compatibility-sensitive — downstream users may build dashboards and alerts on them. Change deliberately.\n204: \n205: ### Key naming rules\n206: \n207: - `snake_case`, not dotted; `tmux_` prefix\n208: - Prefer stable scalars; avoid ad-hoc objects\n209: - Heavy keys (`tmux_stdout`, `tmux_stderr`) are DEBUG-only; consider companion `tmux_stdout_len` fields or hard truncation (e.g. `stdout[:100]`)\n210: \n211: ### Lazy formatting\n212: \n213: `logger.debug(\"msg %s\", val)` not f-strings. Two rationales:\n214: - Deferred string interpolation: skipped entirely when level is filtered\n215: - Aggregator message template grouping: `\"Running %s\"` is one signature grouped ×10,000; f-strings make each line unique\n216: \n217: When computing `val` itself is expensive, guard with `if logger.isEnabledFor(logging.DEBUG)`.\n218: \n219: ### stacklevel for wrappers\n220: \n221: Increment for each wrapper layer so `%(filename)s:%(lineno)d` and OTel `code.filepath` point to the real caller. Verify whenever call depth changes.\n222: \n223: ### LoggerAdapter for persistent context\n224: \n225: For objects with stable identity (Session, Window, Pane), use `LoggerAdapter` to avoid repeating the same `extra` on every call. Lead with the portable pattern (override `process()` to merge); `merge_extra=True` simplifies this on Python 3.13+.\n226: \n227: ### Log levels\n228: \n229: | Level | Use for | Examples |\n230: |-------|---------|----------|\n231: | `DEBUG` | Internal mechanics, tmux I/O, config expansion | tmux command + stdout, trickle-down steps |\n232: | `INFO` | Session lifecycle, user-visible operations | Session created, window added, workspace loaded |\n233: | `WARNING` | Recoverable issues, deprecation, user-actionable config | Deprecated key, missing optional program |\n234: | `ERROR` | Failures that stop an operation | tmux command failed, config validation error |\n235: \n236: Config discovery noise belongs in `DEBUG`; only surprising/user-actionable config issues → `WARNING`.\n237: \n238: ### Message style\n239: \n240: - Lowercase, past tense for events: `\"session created\"`, `\"tmux command failed\"`\n241: - No trailing punctuation\n242: - Keep messages short; put details in `extra`, not the message string\n243: \n244: ### Exception logging\n245: \n246: - Use `logger.exception()` only inside `except` blocks when you are **not** re-raising\n247: - Use `logger.error(..., exc_info=True)` when you need the traceback outside an `except` block\n248: - Avoid `logger.exception()` followed by `raise` — this duplicates the traceback. Either add context via `extra` that would otherwise be lost, or let the exception propagate\n249: \n250: ### Testing logs\n251: \n252: Assert on `caplog.records` attributes, not string matching on `caplog.text`:\n253: - Scope capture: `caplog.at_level(logging.DEBUG, logger=\"libtmux.common\")`\n254: - Filter records rather than index by position: `[r for r in caplog.records if hasattr(r, \"tmux_cmd\")]`\n255: - Assert on schema: `record.tmux_exit_code == 0` not `\"exit code 0\" in caplog.text`\n256: - `caplog.record_tuples` cannot access extra fields — always use `caplog.records`\n257: \n258: ### Output channels\n259: \n260: Two output channels serve different audiences:\n261: \n262: 1. **Diagnostics** (`logger.*()` with `extra`): System events for log files, `caplog`, and aggregators. Never styled.\n263: 2. **User-facing output**: What the human sees. Styled via `Colors` class.\n264:    - Commands with output modes (`--json`/`--ndjson`): prefer `OutputFormatter.emit_text()` from `tmuxp.cli._output` — silenced in non-human modes.\n265:    - Human-only commands: use `tmuxp_echo()` from `tmuxp.log` (re-exported via `tmuxp.cli.utils`) for user-facing messages.\n266:    - **Undefined contracts:** Machine-output behavior for error and empty-result paths (e.g., `search` with no matches) is not yet defined. These paths currently emit styled text through `formatter.emit_text()`, which is a no-op in machine modes.\n267: \n268: Raw `print()` is forbidden in command/business logic. The `print()` call lives only inside the presenter layer (`_output.py`) or `tmuxp_echo`.\n269: \n270: ### Avoid\n271: \n272: - f-strings/`.format()` in log calls\n273: - Unguarded logging in hot loops (guard with `isEnabledFor()`)\n274: - Catch-log-reraise without adding new context\n275: - `print()` for debugging or internal diagnostics — use `logger.debug()` with structured `extra` instead\n276: - Logging secret env var values (log key names only)\n277: - Non-scalar ad-hoc objects in `extra`\n278: - Requiring custom `extra` fields in format strings without safe defaults (missing keys raise `KeyError`)\n279: \n280: ## Doctests\n281: \n282: **All functions and methods MUST have working doctests.** Doctests serve as both documentation and tests.\n283: \n284: **CRITICAL RULES:**\n285: - Doctests MUST actually execute - never comment out function calls or similar\n286: - Doctests MUST NOT be converted to `.. code-block::` as a workaround (code-blocks don't run)\n287: - If you cannot create a working doctest, **STOP and ask for help**\n288: \n289: **Available tools for doctests:**\n290: - `doctest_namespace` fixtures: `server`, `session`, `window`, `pane`, `tmp_path`, `test_utils`\n291: - Ellipsis for variable output: `# doctest: +ELLIPSIS`\n292: - Update `conftest.py` to add new fixtures to `doctest_namespace`\n293: \n294: **`# doctest: +SKIP` is NOT permitted** - it's just another workaround that doesn't test anything. Use the fixtures properly - tmux is required to run tests anyway.\n295: \n296: **Using fixtures in doctests:**\n297: ```python\n298: >>> from tmuxp.workspace.builder import WorkspaceBuilder\n299: >>> config = {'session_name': 'test', 'windows': [{'window_name': 'main'}]}\n300: >>> builder = WorkspaceBuilder(session_config=config, server=server)  # doctest: +ELLIPSIS\n301: >>> builder.build()\n302: >>> builder.session.name\n303: 'test'\n304: ```\n305: \n306: **When output varies, use ellipsis:**\n307: ```python\n308: >>> session.session_id  # doctest: +ELLIPSIS\n309: '$...'\n310: >>> window.window_id  # doctest: +ELLIPSIS\n311: '@...'\n312: ```\n313: \n314: **Additional guidelines:**\n315: 1. **Use narrative descriptions** for test sections rather than inline comments\n316: 2. **Move complex examples** to dedicated test files at `tests/examples/<path>/test_<example>.py`\n317: 3. **Keep doctests simple and focused** on demonstrating usage\n318: 4. **Add blank lines between test sections** for improved readability\n319: \n320: **Doctest exceptions** (patterns where doctests are not required):\n321: \n322: 1. **Sphinx/docutils `visit_*`/`depart_*` methods** - tested via integration tests; 0 examples across docutils (851 methods), Sphinx (800+), and CPython's `ast.NodeVisitor`\n323: 2. **Sphinx `setup()` functions** - entry points not testable in isolation\n324: 3. **Complex recursive traversal functions** - extract helper predicates instead\n325: \n326: **Best practice for node processing**: Extract testable helper functions (like `_is_usage_block()`) and doctest those. Keep complex visitor logic in integration tests.\n327: \n328: ## Documentation Standards\n329: \n330: ### Code Blocks in Documentation\n331: \n332: When writing documentation (README, CHANGES, docs/), follow these rules for code blocks:\n333: \n334: **One command per code block.** This makes commands individually copyable. For sequential commands, either use separate code blocks or chain them with `&&` or `;` and `\\` continuations (keeping it one logical command).\n335: \n336: **Put explanations outside the code block**, not as comments inside.\n337: \n338: Good:\n339: \n340: Run the tests:\n341: \n342: ```console\n343: $ uv run pytest\n344: ```\n345: \n346: Run with coverage:\n347: \n348: ```console\n349: $ uv run pytest --cov\n350: ```\n351: \n352: Bad:\n353: \n354: ```console\n355: # Run the tests\n356: $ uv run pytest\n357: \n358: # Run with coverage\n359: $ uv run pytest --cov\n360: ```\n361: \n362: ### Shell Command Formatting\n363: \n364: These rules apply to shell commands in documentation (README, CHANGES, docs/), **not** to Python doctests.\n365: \n366: **Use `console` language tag with `$ ` prefix.** This distinguishes interactive commands from scripts and enables prompt-aware copy in many terminals.\n367: \n368: Good:\n369: \n370: ```console\n371: $ uv run pytest\n372: ```\n373: \n374: Bad:\n375: \n376: ```bash\n377: uv run pytest\n378: ```\n379: \n380: **Split long commands with `\\` for readability.** Each flag or flag+value pair gets its own continuation line, indented. Positional parameters go on the final line.\n381: \n382: Good:\n383: \n384: ```console\n385: $ pipx install \\\n386:     --suffix=@next \\\n387:     --pip-args '\\--pre' \\\n388:     --force \\\n389:     'tmuxp'\n390: ```\n391: \n392: Bad:\n393: \n394: ```console\n395: $ pipx install --suffix=@next --pip-args '\\--pre' --force 'tmuxp'\n396: ```\n397: \n398: ## Important Notes\n399: \n400: - **QA every edit**: Run formatting and tests before committing\n401: - **Minimum Python**: 3.10+ (per pyproject.toml)\n402: - **Minimum tmux**: 3.2+ (as per README)\n403: \n404: ## CLI Color Semantics (Revision 1, 2026-01-04)\n405: \n406: The CLI uses semantic colors via the `Colors` class in `src/tmuxp/_internal/colors.py`. Colors are chosen based on **hierarchy level** and **semantic meaning**, not just data type.\n407: \n408: ### Design Principles\n409: \n410: 1. **Structural hierarchy**: Headers > Items > Details\n411: 2. **Semantic meaning**: What IS this element?\n412: 3. **Visual weight**: What should draw the eye first?\n413: 4. **Depth separation**: Parent elements should visually contain children\n414: \n415: Inspired by patterns from **jq** (object keys vs values), **ripgrep** (path/line/match distinction), and **mise/just** (semantic method names).\n416: \n417: ### Hierarchy-Based Colors\n418: \n419: | Level | Element Type | Method | Color | Examples |\n420: |-------|--------------|--------|-------|----------|\n421: | **L0** | Section headers | `heading()` | Bright cyan + bold | \"Local workspaces:\", \"Global workspaces:\" |\n422: | **L1** | Primary content | `highlight()` | Magenta + bold | Workspace names (braintree, .tmuxp) |\n423: | **L2** | Supplementary info | `info()` | Cyan | Paths (~/.tmuxp, ~/project/.tmuxp.yaml) |\n424: | **L3** | Metadata/labels | `muted()` | Blue | Source labels (Legacy:, XDG default:) |\n425: \n426: ### Status-Based Colors (Override hierarchy when applicable)\n427: \n428: | Status | Method | Color | Examples |\n429: |--------|--------|-------|----------|\n430: | Success/Active | `success()` | Green | \"active\", \"18 workspaces\" |\n431: | Warning | `warning()` | Yellow | Deprecation notices |\n432: | Error | `error()` | Red | Error messages |\n433: \n434: ### Example Output\n435: \n436: ```\n437: Local workspaces:                              ← heading() bright_cyan+bold\n438:   .tmuxp  ~/work/python/tmuxp/.tmuxp.yaml      ← highlight() + info()\n439: \n440: Global workspaces (~/.tmuxp):                  ← heading() + info()\n441:   braintree                                    ← highlight()\n442:   cihai                                        ← highlight()\n443: \n444: Global workspace directories:                  ← heading()\n445:   Legacy: ~/.tmuxp (18 workspaces, active)     ← muted() + info() + success()\n446:   XDG default: ~/.config/tmuxp (not found)     ← muted() + info() + muted()\n447: ```\n448: \n449: ### Available Methods\n450: \n451: ```python\n452: colors = Colors()\n453: colors.heading(\"Section:\")      # Cyan + bold (section headers)\n454: colors.highlight(\"item\")        # Magenta + bold (primary content)\n455: colors.info(\"/path/to/file\")    # Cyan (paths, supplementary info)\n456: colors.muted(\"label:\")          # Blue (metadata, labels)\n457: colors.success(\"ok\")            # Green (success states)\n458: colors.warning(\"caution\")       # Yellow (warnings)\n459: colors.error(\"failed\")          # Red (errors)\n460: ```\n461: \n462: ### Key Rules\n463: \n464: **Never use the same color for adjacent hierarchy levels.** If headers and items are both blue, they blend together. Each level must be visually distinct.\n465: \n466: **Avoid dim/faint styling.** The ANSI dim attribute (`\\x1b[2m`) is too dark to read on black terminal backgrounds. This includes both standard and bright color variants with dim.\n467: \n468: **Bold may not render distinctly.** Some terminal/font combinations don't differentiate bold from normal weight. Don't rely on bold alone for visual distinction - pair it with color differences.\n\n(End of file - total 468 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AGENTS.md\n\nThis file provides guidance to AI agents (e.g., Claude Code, Cursor, and other LLM-powered tools) when working with code in this repository.\n\n## Project Overview\n\ntmuxp is a session manager for tmux that allows users to save and load tmux sessions through YAML/JSON configuration files. It's powered by libtmux and provides a declarative way to manage tmux sessions.\n\n## Development Commands\n\n### Testing\n- `just test` or `uv run py.test` - Run all tests\n- `uv run py.test tests/path/to/test.py::TestClass::test_method` - Run a single test\n- `uv run ptw .` - Continuous test runner with pytest-watcher\n- `uv run ptw . --now --doctest-modules` - Watch tests including doctests\n- `just start` or `just watch-test` - Watch and run tests on file changes\n\n### Code Quality\n- `just ruff` or `uv run ruff check .` - Run linter\n- `uv run ruff check . --fix --show-fixes` - Fix linting issues automatically","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"AGENTS.md","time":{"start":1775777673755,"end":1775777673767}}}]}
